# SecureData Archive Mermaid Architecture

These diagrams describe the current codebase, not an idealized version. Key facts reflected here:

- Browser owns the user private keys: WebAuthn passkey, ECDH data-decryption key, and ECDSA Fabric-signing key.
- `server.py` verifies auth, sanitizes metadata, talks to AI/IPFS/Fabric CA, and orchestrates Fabric signing flows, but does not hold user private keys.
- User Fabric transactions use offline signing: backend prepares proposal/transaction bytes, browser signs locally, backend submits signed bytes through the Go helper.
- Service transactions use the unified Go HTTP agent on `:8090` with `AGENT_TOKEN`; `X-Agent-Role` selects `SecurityService`, `MLService`, or `RiskService`.
- Chaincode forces new assets to `Unverified`; AI suggestions remain advisory until owner approval.

## Main Diagram

```mermaid
flowchart TB
    User["User / SecurityService / Researcher"]

    subgraph Browser["Browser on http://localhost:8000"]
        UI["Static UI<br/>index.html + frontend/app/*.js"]
        WebAuthn["WebAuthn passkey<br/>authenticator private key"]
        LocalKeys["IndexedDB local key store<br/>ECDH data key + ECDSA Fabric key"]
        ClientCrypto["WebCrypto / CryptoJS / JSEncrypt<br/>content encryption, key wrapping, signing"]
        AgentRPC["agentEval / agentSubmit<br/>backend-routed Fabric RPC"]
    end

    subgraph Backend["Flask backend server.py on :5500"]
        Auth["Auth/session layer<br/>WebAuthn verify, CSRF, invites, audit"]
        UploadAPI["/upload<br/>filename, envelope, AAD checks"]
